\p{
  Similarly, for #{\xi\in\mathcal{F}_S} and any object #{S'} of #{\mathcal{C}} over
  ##{
    G_\xi(S')
    = \Aut(\xi\times_S S'),
  }
  we thus define a contravariant functor #{G_\xi} from #{\mathcal{C}_S} to the category of groups.
  \oldpage{190-14}
  With this setup, we claim that \em{#{Z^1(S'/S,G)} is canonically identified with the set of descent data on #{\xi'=\xi\times_S S'} with respect to #{S'\to S}} (\ref{fga3.i-a.1-definition-1.6}), and that \em{#{\HH^1(S'/S,G)} can be identified with the set of isomorphism classes of objects of #{\mathcal{F}_{S'}} endowed with a descent data relative to #{\alpha\colon S'\to S} that are isomorphic, as objects of #{\mathcal{F}_{S'}}, to #{\xi'=\xi\times_S S'}}.
  Then, \em{if #{\alpha\colon S'\to S} is an #{\mathcal{F}}-descent morphism} (cf. \ref{fga3.i-a.4.b}), \em{then #{\HH^1(S'/S,G)} contains as a subset the set of isomorphism classes of objects #{\eta} of #{\mathcal{F}_S} such that #{\eta\times_S S'} is isomorphic (in #{\mathcal{F}_{S'}}) to #{\xi\times_S S'}};
  further, \em{this inclusion is the identity if and only if every descent data on #{\xi'=\xi\times_S S'} with respect to #{\alpha\colon S'\to S} is effective}.
  (This will be the case, in particular, if #{\alpha\colon S'\to S} is a strict #{S}-descent morphism).
}

